Macedonians vote in referendum to change their country's name
Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum on Saturday on whether to change their country's name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that could resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that has blocked the opening of EU and NATO accession talks.
There is a province in Greece called Macedonia, and Greece claims that the name of its northern neighbor represents its own territory and has vetoed that country's membership in NATO and the EU.
The two governments agreed on the proposed new name in June, but nationalist opponents claim that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has stated that he will not vote in the referendum, and the campaign to boycott the vote cast doubt on whether turnout would meet the minimum 50 percent required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the referendum ballot read: "Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to allow Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged after the breakup of Yugoslavia, to join bodies such as the EU and NATO.
'Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia so that they can live freely under the aegis of the European Union because it means safer lives for all of us', said Olivera Georgijevska (79) in Skopje.
Although the result of the vote is not legally binding, enough members of parliament said they would respect it to be considered decisive.
A change of name requires a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The State Election Commission has stated that no irregularities have been reported as of 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66% of registered voters voted.
"I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe", said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter from the capital Skopje.
The Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dusko, in Strumica on 30 September 2018, approached a referendum on changing the country's name, which would pave the way for joining the NATO alliance and the European Union.
54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov set up a small stage in front of the parliament in Skopje and moved chairs in front of tents set up by those boycotting the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads held high, not as servants", Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don't want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of Eurasian integration.
Prime Minister Zaev said NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, a country with an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
"I believe that the vast majority will support the referendum, as more than 80 percent of our citizens support the EU and NATO", Zaev said after the vote.
He said a "positive" result would be "a confirmation of our future".
A poll released last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Research shows that between 30 and 43 percent of voters will participate in the referendum, which is below the required response.
Another poll, conducted by Macedonian Telma TV, showed that 57 percent of respondents intend to vote on Sunday.
Of that number, 70 percent said they would support the referendum.
For the referendum to be successful, turnout must be 50 percent plus one vote.
A failed referendum would represent the first serious blow to the pro-Western government's policies since it took office in May last year.
