The Scottish Independent Schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test scores, with added weight given to individual and collective achievements in sport, the arts, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further education and higher education, careers they want, and to make them citizens of the world.
As an education sector that can design and implement the above curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be the preferred and preferred subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his native language, it goes to his heart.
This statement is a powerful reminder that we cannot use English alone if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of this year's final exams show that the highest marks in languages were achieved by students from independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received excellent grades.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils achieved an excellent mark for Mandarin, while 72% of pupils learning German, 69% of pupils learning French and 63% of pupils learning Spanish also achieved the highest possible mark.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will surely need in the future.
Today, languages as electives are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and math) in the independent school curriculum, as elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17% of employers were unable to fill jobs due to a lack of a language-skilled workforce.
Language skills are therefore increasingly becoming an imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs demand language skills, these skills are crucial in a globalized world.
Regardless of career choice, people who learn to speak a foreign language will in the future experience the long-term benefits of such a skill.
A person who speaks several languages can communicate directly with strangers, which gives him an advantage over his competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults, 75% of respondents in the UK do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, more precisely 15%.
So investing in language learning is very important for children today.
Learning more languages, especially those of developing countries, will help children to find good jobs.
In Scotland, every school offers different languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their curriculum, while others will opt for languages that are considered to be the most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, independent schools will always have a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment in which they can learn and prepare themselves with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be ignored that in this age of global business, language skills are very important for the future of any country, and this must be reflected in education.
So knowledge of modern languages really should be seen as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer language choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It has to be done right.
John Edward is headmaster of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
