Students at Harvard take a course on how to get a good rest
A new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to get a good night's sleep in an attempt to combat the growing culture of caffeinated study and sleepless nights.
The academic found that students at the world's best university often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed a course he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea for the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
And at the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said, "Why did I only find out about this now, in my last year of college?"
She said no one had told her how important sleep was, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help with academic and athletic achievement and overall health.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, says that the university decided to introduce the course after students were noticing a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks involved a picture of a student dormitory where students had to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sleep deprivation affects performance, and the importance of a sleep routine.
During the course of the lecture, students also learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Afterwards, a campus map with interactive icons is displayed to encourage students to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect your health", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in studying all night before exams persists, says the professor, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
The professor says that a student's secret weapon against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety should be good quality sleep, which also helps fight obesity because sleep deprivation affects the brain, causing it to starve and become hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student in California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending his first-year lectures at Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to expand the course to the entire campus.
As a next step, it plans to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar course of study before joining a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm during sleep and wakefulness, aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights that can disrupt circadian rhythms and cause sleep problems.
