Tom Daley felt "inferior" when it came to sexuality.
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to others because of his sexuality - but it gave him the motivation to become successful.
The 24-year-old said that until he entered high school, he was not aware that "not everyone is like me".
In his statement to Radio 4 Desert Island Discs, hosted by Lauren Laverne, he said he spoke about gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that winning the Olympics was less important to him since he became a father.
The longtime regular host of the show, Kirsty Young, took a few months off due to illness.
Appearing as a backstabber on Laverne's first show, Daley said that growing up he felt "less valuable" compared to others because "it was not socially acceptable to love both boys and girls".
He said, "To this day, those feelings of inferiority and being different from others have been the real things that have given me the power and the strength to succeed".
He says he wanted to prove he was "somebody and something", so he wouldn't disappoint anyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become a prominent LGBT advocate and used his performance at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said that he spoke publicly because he felt happy to live openly without consequences and because he wanted to give others hope.
The three-time world champion said he was surprised to fall in love with a man - American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013.
Daley married an Oscar winner, who's 20 years older than him, last year, but he said the age difference had never been a problem.
"When you're so young you go through so much", he said, looking back on his first Olympics when he was 14 and his father died of cancer three years later, "it's hard to find someone his age who hasn't had similar ups and downs".
In June, they became the parents of a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "entire perspective" had changed.
"If you asked me last year, the whole story would be about me winning the gold medal", he said.
You know what, there are bigger things than Olympic gold medals.
Robbie is my Olympic gold medal.
His son shares his name with his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at age 40 after being diagnosed with a brain tumor.
Daley said his father couldn't accept that he was going to die, and one of the last things he asked was if they got tickets to London 2012 -- because he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him, 'Dad, you're not gonna be here long enough to be in the front row,'" he said.
"I held his hand as he came out, and it was only when he stopped breathing and died that I finally realized he was not invincible", he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
"I just knew that this was what I had dreamed of my whole life - to jump in front of the home crowd at the Olympics, there was no better feeling", he said.
It was also the inspiration for choosing the first song ̶ Proud by singer Heather Small ̶ which echoed in him during the preparation for the Olympics and which he always raves about.
