German new warship put back on standby
The German Navy's newest frigate was scheduled to be commissioned in 2014 to replace older Cold War-era warships, but won't be ready until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the ship Rheinland-Pfalz, the lead ship of the all-new Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates, has now been delayed until the first half of 2019, Die Zeit reports citing a military spokesman.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but troubling problems after delivery have hit the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels, ordered by the Navy in 2007, will replace the older Bremen-class frigates.
As far as we know, it will have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some invisibility technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
The Commission notes that the new vessels are expected to be deployed in the near future, but that the new vessels will be deployed in the near future.
However, the constant delays mean that the most advanced warships ̶ which are said to allow Germany to show off its power abroad ̶ will become obsolete by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated frigate F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially declined to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of key "software and hardware flaws" that would make the warship useless if sent on a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - half the size of the older Bremen class frigates.
Also, the ship proved to be dramatically overweight, reducing its efficiency and limiting the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne Rhineland-Palatinate is believed to be twice as heavy as similar class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project ̶ including crew training ̶ also becomes a problem.
The price is said to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) ̶ from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
The problems affecting the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that the German naval power is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's Defence Committee, admitted that the navy is actually "running out of ships capable of deployment".
The official said that the problem has increased over time because the old ships have been retired and there are no replacement ships.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Württemberg class frigates could join the navy.
The National Trust is eavesdropping on the secret lives of bats
New research at a Scottish Highland estate aims to discover how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
It is hoped that the results will shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study, conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland (NTS), will follow the common and swamp dwarf bats, as well as the brown long-nosed and river bats in Inverweather Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special cameras will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile scans using handheld detectors.
An expert analysis of the sound of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' voices and what each species is doing.
A habitat map and a report will then be made to create a detailed picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined dramatically over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affect shelter and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as can fly nets and certain chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by pet cats.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, their night-hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to find bugs and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained specialists who regularly conduct surveys, shelter inspections, and occasional rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave's property in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The manager, David Thompson, says the property is an ideal area for them.
"Here in Threave we have a huge space for bats", he said.
We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitats.
However, there is still much we do not know about bats, so the work we are doing here and at other facilities will help us to better understand what they need to thrive".
He stresses the importance of checking for bats before starting maintenance work inside buildings, since the accidental destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and young, likely wiping out the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, torture or harass them or destroy their habitat.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a representative of the Scottish Bat Society, urged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we just don't know how their population is progressing".
